<DIV CLASS="c5"><P CLASS="c30"><SPAN CLASS="c31">n1.&nbsp; The four Asian American victims-turned-defendants were dubbed the &quot;Quincy 4&quot; to build solidarity with the five young African American men who were beaten by the Medford police in 2005. Supporters of the Somerville victims called the group the &quot;Somerville 5.&quot; See, e.g., Phebe Eckfeldt, Racial Profiling is Growing, Workers World, Sept. 21, 2006, http://www.workers.org/2006/us/somerville5-0928; Bill Cunningham, Somerville 5 Jury Returns Mixed Verdict, Bridge News, June 15, 2006, http://bridgenews.org/bridge news/062006/s5trial. Supporters of the Somerville 5 alleged that the incident was indicative of racial profiling and false prosecution. See, e.g., Chuck Turner et al., Support Letter for Somerville 5 Defendants, available at http://www.iacenter.org/polprisoners/somerville5 06282006.htm (last visited Apr. 8, 2008). </SPAN></P>
